   32
   > Appendix

I. Application of central limit theorem

   Let X be the total net amount of loss by the gambler, Y be the total
   amount of wager. Let the expected net

   value of a unit (dollar) wager be Zi = 1-r (i.e., r denotes the house
   edge), and let var(Z i )   2 .

By definition, we have X  Y  ( Z 1  Z 2  Z 3  ...  Z Y ) . Hence, the
mean and variance of X can be

   derived as follows:

   Y
   > E ( X )  Y   E ( Z i ) Y  Y (1  r )  Yr
   > i 1

   Y
   > Var ( X )   Var ( Z i )  Y 2
   > i 1

   Since X is the sum of a series i.i.d. random variables, its density
   converges (in distribution) to a normal

distribution. Thus, we have: X | Y , r ,  2 ~ N (Yr, Y 2 ) .

